# Line endings, and why this file is load-bearing rather than housekeeping.
#
# M5-F measured it: running the analyzer over the same Flutter source with CRLF line endings produces
# **different UIR**. Only `span.length` changes — `line` and `column` are unaffected, and node ids are
# byte-identical, so content addressing (ADR-17) holds — but the document differs:
#
#     LF   uir.ndjson  sha256 7dae021ec9c4e694   span.length 297
#     CRLF uir.ndjson  sha256 1ed8ccf5e0728d0d   span.length 307
#
# A source span measured in characters legitimately counts the `\r`. The problem is not the measurement, it
# is that **a checkout setting would change compiler output**. Git's `core.autocrlf` defaults to `true` on
# Windows, so a Windows contributor would check out CRLF fixtures, and:
#
#   * `dart/bridge_analyzer/test/build_proof_test.dart` byte-compares a committed golden. It would fail.
#   * `fixtures/uir/*.ndjson` would no longer be what the analyzer produces.
#   * Cache keys (Spec §7.2 hashes extraction output) would differ per platform, so nothing would hit.
#
# The fix is to normalise the repository rather than to change what a span means: a span counting its own
# line endings is correct, and rewriting that would be changing the compiler to suit a VCS default.
#
# `text=auto eol=lf` checks every text file out with LF on every platform. Windows editors have handled LF
# for a decade; this is the ordinary setting for a project that hashes its own files.

* text=auto eol=lf

# Goldens: `-text` so git performs **no** conversion in either direction, under any user configuration.
# These are files whose exact bytes are the assertion, and `eol=lf` above would already give them LF —
# this is belt-and-braces for the one class where being wrong is silent.
#
# Fixture Dart *source* is deliberately NOT listed here: it must be normalised to LF like every other
# source file, because it is the analyzer's input and its line endings are what this file exists about.
*.ndjson   -text

# Binary, so git neither diffs nor converts them.
*.png      binary
*.jpg      binary
*.ico      binary
*.woff     binary
*.woff2    binary
*.tgz      binary
